{{Use British English|date=January 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}} {{Infobox Archbishopric |border = catholic |font_color = black |archbishopric = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of St Andrews and Edinburgh|St Andrews and Edinburgh]] |coatofarms = |coat_of_arms_caption = |image = <!-- Image of the current incumbent --> |incumbent = [[Leo Cushley]] |diocese = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of St Andrews and Edinburgh|Archdiocese of St Andrews and Edinburgh]] |cathedral = [[St. Mary's Cathedral, Edinburgh (Catholic)|St Mary's Cathedral, Edinburgh]] |website = }} The '''Archbishop of St Andrews and Edinburgh''' is the [[Ordinary (officer)|ordinary]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of St Andrews and Edinburgh]]. The archdiocese covers an area of 5,504&nbsp;km². The [[Metropolitan see]] is in the [[Edinburgh|City of Edinburgh]] where the archbishop's seat (''[[cathedra]]'') is located at the [[St. Mary's Cathedral, Edinburgh (Catholic)|Cathedral Church of Saint Mary]].<ref name=dsaae/><ref name=gigastandrewsedin/> The 8th and current archbishop is [[Leo Cushley]].<ref name="bbc-enthroned">{{cite news|title=Monsignor Leo Cushley installed as Archbishop of St Andrews and Edinburgh|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-24174503|accessdate=21 September 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=21 September 2013}}</ref>
== History == After the [[Scottish Reformation]], the [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic Church]] abandoned the hierarchy and for nearly a century Roman Catholics in Scotland were under the jurisdiction of the English [[Apostolic prefect|prefects]] and [[vicars apostolic]].<ref name=cathstaedin>{{Catholic|no-icon=1|prescript=|wstitle=Archdiocese of Saint Andrews and Edinburgh}}</ref> In 1653, the [[Apostolic prefect|Prefecture Apostolic]] of Scotland was established, which was elevated to the [[Apostolic vicariate|Vicariate Apostolic]] in 1694.<ref name=cathstaedin/> On 23 July 1727, Scotland was divided into the Vicariates Apostolic of the Lowland District and the Highland District, each headed by a vicar apostolic.<ref name=dsaae/><ref name=gigastandrewsedin/><ref>{{Harvnb|Brady|1876}}, ''The Episcopal Succession in England, Scotland and Ireland, volume 3'', p. 459.</ref> On 13 February 1827, Scotland was divided again into three vicariates apostolic; the Eastern District (formerly the Lowland District), the Northern District (formerly the Highland District), and the Western District (created from parts of the other two districts).<ref name=dsaae/><ref name=gigastandrewsedin/><ref>{{Harvnb|Brady|1876}}, ''The Episcopal Succession in England, Scotland and Ireland, volume 3'', p. 468.</ref> On the [[restoration of the Scottish hierarchy]] by [[Pope Leo XIII]] on 15 March 1878, part of the Eastern District was elevated to the status of a metropolitan archdiocese with the title St Andrews and Edinburgh.<ref name=dsaae/><ref name=gigastandrewsedin/>
